00:00:06.201 --> 00:00:06.910
- Hello.

00:00:06.910 --> 00:00:07.970
Welcome.

00:00:07.970 --> 00:00:11.620
My name's John Huth,
and I'm your host today.

00:00:11.620 --> 00:00:14.340
I'm Radcliffe Ventures's
faculty member,

00:00:14.340 --> 00:00:17.780
which means I help Radcliffe
do a variety of programming

00:00:17.780 --> 00:00:21.080
here, most notably the
science programming.

00:00:21.080 --> 00:00:24.620
This is the last in a series
of lectures on the ocean.

00:00:24.620 --> 00:00:26.910
This is a thematic
year about oceans.

00:00:26.910 --> 00:00:28.670
We had a symposium,
a science symposium,

00:00:28.670 --> 00:00:31.250
on oceans in the
fall, and we've had

00:00:31.250 --> 00:00:34.970
a number of topics that
are pertinent to oceans

00:00:34.970 --> 00:00:35.980
throughout the year.

00:00:35.980 --> 00:00:37.730
This is the last of these.

00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:41.810
The title of this talk is
"More Oceans, Less Plastic"

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.200
by Anna Cummins, who is the
co-founder of the 5 Gyres

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:46.250
Institute.

00:00:46.250 --> 00:00:49.580
And because I guess
I'm introducing,

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:52.010
I get to blather on just
a little bit, so you'll

00:00:52.010 --> 00:00:53.540
have to forgive me, OK?

00:00:53.540 --> 00:00:57.960
So this is a topic near
and dear to my heart.

00:00:57.960 --> 00:01:00.740
I'm a sea kayaker and a member
of the Main Island Trail

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:01.400
Association.

00:01:01.400 --> 00:01:03.770
We have three
members over there.

00:01:03.770 --> 00:01:07.340
And every year we
participate in a cleanup

00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:09.360
of some of the main islands.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:12.680
So we go out on a skiff,
get a bunch of garbage bags.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:13.790
We scour the ground.

00:01:13.790 --> 00:01:16.940
And what we see is
a ton of plastic.

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:19.220
I mean, you wouldn't
believe how much there is.

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:22.059
Lobstermen, they all
take a bleach bottle.

00:01:22.059 --> 00:01:23.600
They'll rinse off
their deck and just

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:27.770
toss it out in the Gulf
of Maine or oil bottles.

00:01:27.770 --> 00:01:30.170
And this is most of the
stuff that we clean up.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:33.017
And it's rather amazing,
because they don't even

00:01:33.017 --> 00:01:34.850
realize that they're
tossing the stuff where

00:01:34.850 --> 00:01:37.430
they earn their living.

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:40.280
And it's a bit
unfathomable, but it

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:43.280
says that they probably think
that is an infinite resource

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:46.850
and it's not exhaustible.

00:01:46.850 --> 00:01:48.740
So that's one thing that
I found of interest.

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:51.807
Another one was there
was a recent paper that

00:01:51.807 --> 00:01:53.390
was published that
was in the New York

00:01:53.390 --> 00:01:58.010
Times about the discovery
of large amounts of plastic

00:01:58.010 --> 00:02:00.920
in the Arctic Ocean were
being transported there

00:02:00.920 --> 00:02:04.220
through a kind of current called
a thermohaline current which

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:05.970
is not a typical
surface current,

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:09.259
but it has to do with salinity.

00:02:09.259 --> 00:02:11.810
And I should mention
that this was

00:02:11.810 --> 00:02:15.690
found through the work of,
partly, Chris Bowler, who

00:02:15.690 --> 00:02:16.940
I don't think is here.

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:19.790
But he's a fellow at the
Radcliffe Institute this year,

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:23.480
and he runs an
expedition vessel called

00:02:23.480 --> 00:02:25.520
the Tara that found this.

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:29.210
And so as you'll
probably hear, there

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:32.990
are five subtropical
gyres in the oceans.

00:02:32.990 --> 00:02:35.690
However, there is a sixth
gyre called the Beaufort

00:02:35.690 --> 00:02:37.250
Gyre in the Arctic Ocean.

00:02:37.250 --> 00:02:39.655
So you might have to
change the name to sixth--

00:02:39.655 --> 00:02:40.550
- There are 11 gyres.

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:41.060
- There are 11?

00:02:41.060 --> 00:02:41.650
- Yes.

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:42.230
- OK.

00:02:42.230 --> 00:02:42.520
OK.

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:43.478
Well I stand corrected.

00:02:43.478 --> 00:02:44.089
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:44.089 --> 00:02:46.130
This is why I'm here to
listen, and I should just

00:02:46.130 --> 00:02:47.510
keep my big mouth shut.

00:02:47.510 --> 00:02:49.460
Thank you.

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:52.797
OK, so Anna, she's
been spending 20 years

00:02:52.797 --> 00:02:54.755
studying and protecting
the oceans in undergrad

00:02:54.755 --> 00:02:58.340
at Stanford, master's
from Monterey Institute

00:02:58.340 --> 00:03:02.090
for International Affairs,
a Sustainable Communities

00:03:02.090 --> 00:03:03.440
Leadership Fellowship.

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:08.330
In 2009, she founded the 5
Gyres with Marcus Eriksen.

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:12.214
And since the founding, she
spent a huge number of trips,

00:03:12.214 --> 00:03:14.630
and one in particular that I
look forward to hearing about

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:16.790
is on a junk raft out of Hawaii.

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:19.583
So without any
further ado, Anna.

00:03:19.583 --> 00:03:22.529
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:25.700
- Well, thank you so much.

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:27.950
Thank you, especially,
to John, and to Linda,

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:30.440
and all the people, the
staff who made this possible

00:03:30.440 --> 00:03:31.910
and brought me out here today.

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:33.691
I wonder how many
people can say that they

00:03:33.691 --> 00:03:35.690
were given the floor at
one of our nation's most

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:37.790
prestigious institutes
to talk trash.

00:03:37.790 --> 00:03:39.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:41.270
But in all seriousness,
at 5 Gyres,

00:03:41.270 --> 00:03:42.907
we really appreciate
the opportunity

00:03:42.907 --> 00:03:44.990
to share some of our
research with your community,

00:03:44.990 --> 00:03:47.900
and hopefully not inspire
guilt, but hopefully

00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:51.340
inspire new thoughts and
ideas about solutions.

00:03:51.340 --> 00:03:53.270
So when I first was
exposed to this issue

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:56.360
of plastic pollution
in 2001, it was barely

00:03:56.360 --> 00:03:58.670
a blip on the public radar.

00:03:58.670 --> 00:04:01.130
I was a student at the time
at the Middlebury Institute

00:04:01.130 --> 00:04:04.020
for International Studies
in Monterey, California,

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:06.560
which is known as a hotbed
for marine conservation

00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:07.820
around the world.

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:11.390
And it was at this time that
I heard a lecture, in 2001,

00:04:11.390 --> 00:04:13.760
from a man named Captain
Charles Moore who

00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:16.380
was a hero in my world
of plastic pollution.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:18.649
He was the first to really
go out into the gyre

00:04:18.649 --> 00:04:20.919
and bring this to the
public's attention.

00:04:20.919 --> 00:04:22.460
But what's really
interesting to note

00:04:22.460 --> 00:04:25.700
is that the research in
the literature on plastic

00:04:25.700 --> 00:04:28.550
predates Charlie
Moore's work by decades.

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:31.640
Some of the first reports and
observations about plastic

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:35.780
impacting marine life date
back to the '60s and the '70s,

00:04:35.780 --> 00:04:39.380
the first major publication
in Science Magazine

00:04:39.380 --> 00:04:42.830
in the early '70s on plastic
in the North Atlantic.

00:04:42.830 --> 00:04:45.320
But as never happens
in the academic world,

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:49.080
these studies pretty
much sat on a shelf--

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:51.950
oh my goodness-- sat on
a shelf, gathering dust,

00:04:51.950 --> 00:04:55.070
until Charlie went out and
gathered the first samples,

00:04:55.070 --> 00:04:57.470
brought them back,
samples like this,

00:04:57.470 --> 00:04:59.810
and media really began
to pay attention.

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:01.850
So that was in 2001.

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:04.730
I left this lecture
absolutely horrified by what

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:05.720
I was hearing--

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.900
both by the content
but also by the fact

00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:10.610
that no one was really
talking about this

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:11.700
in my graduate program.

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:13.700
Nobody knew about it.

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:17.490
So fast forward
now 16 years later,

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:21.410
there is a global movement
now around plastic pollution.

00:05:21.410 --> 00:05:24.080
Major institutes from the
Ellen MacArthur Foundation,

00:05:24.080 --> 00:05:27.080
to the United Nations,
to major corporations

00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:31.220
like Dell and Unilever, people
are now paying attention.

00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:33.380
There is a movement
called the Break Free

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:37.700
from Plastic Movement, which now
encompasses more than 800 NGOs.

00:05:37.700 --> 00:05:39.560
So there really is
some traction now,

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:42.110
and the awareness is
getting out in a big way.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:45.890
We've had federal legislation
passed and lots of wins.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:48.440
But at the same time,
as the movement grows

00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:50.100
and as more public
pay attention,

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:53.060
and as there's pushback
from the community,

00:05:53.060 --> 00:05:57.360
the opposition is right
there getting equally strong.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:00.410
To give you an idea of what
we're up against, in 2014,

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:04.310
we produced around 311
million tons of plastic,

00:06:04.310 --> 00:06:08.280
and those numbers are expected
to triple in the next 50 years.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:11.060
So we have a long way to go, and
some of the same interests that

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:15.170
serve the most to profit
by this are the same ones

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:18.680
that are using, at times,
some pretty dirty tactics

00:06:18.680 --> 00:06:20.600
to fight us.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:26.660
So with that, I
wanted to also mention

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:30.650
that we're now seeing new
signs of this opposition

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:34.010
between industry and the
environmental movement that

00:06:34.010 --> 00:06:36.420
date back many, many years.

00:06:36.420 --> 00:06:38.900
But before I go further,
I want to do something

00:06:38.900 --> 00:06:41.466
that parents, especially
newly enamored parents,

00:06:41.466 --> 00:06:42.840
do a little too
often, and that's

00:06:42.840 --> 00:06:44.980
share photos of
their little ones.

00:06:44.980 --> 00:06:47.450
I've managed to include her
in every presentation I've

00:06:47.450 --> 00:06:48.760
given for the last four years.

00:06:48.760 --> 00:06:50.690
So thank you for indulging me.

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:52.430
But to me, she
represents what's really

00:06:52.430 --> 00:06:54.800
at stake for the
next generation.

00:06:54.800 --> 00:06:56.300
What sort of quality
of life will we

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:58.520
expect for the next generation?

00:06:58.520 --> 00:07:00.050
I love bringing her to nature.

00:07:00.050 --> 00:07:02.810
I especially love
bringing her to the beach.

00:07:02.810 --> 00:07:06.549
And I wonder how I will
explain this to her.

00:07:06.549 --> 00:07:08.090
So anyone who has
been to Los Angeles

00:07:08.090 --> 00:07:09.260
might recognize this beach.

00:07:09.260 --> 00:07:11.593
This was the same beach where
I used to play as a child.

00:07:11.593 --> 00:07:13.786
You can see the Santa Monica
Pier in the background.

00:07:13.786 --> 00:07:15.410
Now, it normally
doesn't look like this

00:07:15.410 --> 00:07:18.200
because it is a very
popular tourist attraction.

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:20.460
And immediately,
after a big rain,

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:22.880
the sweepers and trucks will
be out there to make sure

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:25.570
that the public
doesn't see this.

00:07:25.570 --> 00:07:27.440
And as a kid, on
this same beach,

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:29.750
I would go and
wander around looking

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:31.550
for seashells and rocks.

00:07:31.550 --> 00:07:35.150
Today, I cannot walk this beach
or really virtually any beach

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:38.150
that I've been to anywhere in
the world without finding trace

00:07:38.150 --> 00:07:40.040
levels of plastic.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:42.860
Now, we with 5 Gyres had a
chance over the last eight

00:07:42.860 --> 00:07:47.060
years to conduct 17 expeditions
around the world's oceans,

00:07:47.060 --> 00:07:49.280
collect over 600 samples.

00:07:49.280 --> 00:07:53.180
And I have a few basic
observations I wanted to bring.

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:55.400
And that is, where
there is sea water,

00:07:55.400 --> 00:07:57.890
there is plastic, which is
a pretty remarkable thing

00:07:57.890 --> 00:08:00.710
to be able to say, given that
plastics have only really been

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:03.970
popular for the last 100 years.

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:06.980
Of those 600 samples
I mentioned, only two

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:09.020
have come up free of plastic.

00:08:09.020 --> 00:08:12.380
And this was at a time when
we weren't using high tech

00:08:12.380 --> 00:08:14.360
research equipment to
look for microfibrils

00:08:14.360 --> 00:08:16.640
or nanoparticles of plastic.

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:19.920
Second, that plastic
pollution is a design flaw,

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:23.150
and I think this is really
important messaging.

00:08:23.150 --> 00:08:26.200
I'm going to share solutions
later, after I horrify you

00:08:26.200 --> 00:08:27.610
with all the gory bits.

00:08:27.610 --> 00:08:30.700
And it's important to come
back to the messaging.

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:33.850
How is the messaging about
plastic being portrayed to us?

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:35.679
Who is responsible
or shouldn't be

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:38.049
responsible for
plastic pollution?

00:08:38.049 --> 00:08:40.390
Third, and this kind
of goes hand-in-hand

00:08:40.390 --> 00:08:43.510
with plastic pollution
being a design flaw,

00:08:43.510 --> 00:08:47.770
and that is that solutions
must begin upstream.

00:08:47.770 --> 00:08:51.610
We've taken this material,
fossil fuel based, incredibly

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:54.730
valuable, and we use it to
make things that we throw away

00:08:54.730 --> 00:08:55.840
after one time.

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:58.930
And that not only makes
poor environmental sense,

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:03.110
it makes some very
poor economic sense.

00:09:03.110 --> 00:09:07.882
So how did we get here in
such a short period of time?

00:09:07.882 --> 00:09:10.090
I like beginning with this
image, because this really

00:09:10.090 --> 00:09:13.030
encapsulates our
thinking about plastic.

00:09:13.030 --> 00:09:16.750
So this was the cover of
Life Magazine in 1955.

00:09:16.750 --> 00:09:19.840
This article was titled
"Throwaway Living."

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:21.610
And the copy in
this article said,

00:09:21.610 --> 00:09:24.370
"The objects you see flying
around in this picture

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:27.160
would normally take
40 hours to clean

00:09:27.160 --> 00:09:29.350
except no housewife
need bother,"

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:32.530
because we can just
throw it all away.

00:09:32.530 --> 00:09:38.200
Now, we talk today about, where
is this place called "away"?

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:40.990
Something I found recently,
after showing this photo

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:43.434
many, many, many times,
is the cleanup that

00:09:43.434 --> 00:09:45.100
happened after this
photo, which I think

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:47.410
is equally fascinating
and prophetic,

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:48.550
when you think about it.

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:51.790
Because this stuff doesn't
just disappear into thin air.

00:09:51.790 --> 00:09:53.710
It all has to go somewhere.

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:56.380
We began seeing evidence
of this as early

00:09:56.380 --> 00:09:58.780
as the '60s and the '70s.

00:09:58.780 --> 00:10:02.170
And no sooner did the first
examples of plastic pollution

00:10:02.170 --> 00:10:04.450
littering roadsides
start to become

00:10:04.450 --> 00:10:07.834
an issue when a trade
group came into being,

00:10:07.834 --> 00:10:09.250
a nonprofit group
came into being,

00:10:09.250 --> 00:10:12.040
called Keep America Beautiful
with funding provided

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:15.130
by Coca-Cola and Pepsi and
some of the same interests

00:10:15.130 --> 00:10:17.710
that really wanted to
keep us from staying

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:20.170
using a reusable,
refillable system,

00:10:20.170 --> 00:10:22.120
and moving to disposables.

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:25.460
One of their first big very
successful ad campaigns,

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:29.860
I'm sure many people
here will recognize.

00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:33.340
I want to show this photo not
to suggest that this didn't have

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:35.140
a great impact,
because there are

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:38.230
a lot of statistics about
how litter abatement really

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:38.920
improved.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:42.040
People were littering
less after this campaign.

00:10:42.040 --> 00:10:43.630
But coming back to messaging--

00:10:43.630 --> 00:10:46.130
I don't know if you can see in
the bottom right hand corner.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:48.340
It says, "People
start pollution,

00:10:48.340 --> 00:10:50.140
so people can stop it."

00:10:50.140 --> 00:10:52.840
And that messaging right
there diverted attention

00:10:52.840 --> 00:10:55.510
from the system, that
we were switching

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:58.090
from a reusable system
to a disposable system.

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:01.330
Instead it put the onus of
responsibility on the public.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:02.380
It's a people problem.

00:11:02.380 --> 00:11:03.580
It's people littering.

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:05.680
It has nothing to
do with design.

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:07.630
And here in lies a big
part of the problem

00:11:07.630 --> 00:11:10.180
that we're still facing today.

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:12.820
Now, starting in the
'50s, we saw an explosion

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:15.430
of plastic being produced.

00:11:15.430 --> 00:11:18.400
It did start fairly
innocently in that some

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:21.130
of the early prototypes for
plastic came from a response

00:11:21.130 --> 00:11:25.450
to things like precious
resources being overused,

00:11:25.450 --> 00:11:27.910
ivory from elephants
and shellac and rubber

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:30.110
and all these different things.

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:33.640
And then we saw a boom
during World War II, a boom

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:35.770
for plastic production.

00:11:35.770 --> 00:11:38.050
And that coupled with
a lot of messaging

00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:40.840
about how we needed to
stimulate the economy with lots

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:43.210
of consumption was
the perfect marriage

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:46.250
for plastic and disposable
plastics to come into being.

00:11:46.250 --> 00:11:50.890
So you can see the
skyrocketing of production to,

00:11:50.890 --> 00:11:54.670
I mentioned before, today,
311 million tons of plastic

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:58.870
expected to double and triple
in the next 25 to 50 years.

00:11:58.870 --> 00:12:03.220
But what has not kept pace
with this extreme explosion

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:07.600
of production is our ability
to recover and recycle,

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:09.970
and there's a lot to
say about recycling.

00:12:09.970 --> 00:12:12.130
But starting there, so
out of that big number

00:12:12.130 --> 00:12:16.930
there, around 78 million tons
of that are for packaging.

00:12:16.930 --> 00:12:21.310
Of that, only 14% is
recovered, and I'm not

00:12:21.310 --> 00:12:22.510
going to say recycled.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:27.550
Of that 14%, only 2% is truly
recycled in a closed loop

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:28.630
system.

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:30.610
So where is the rest going?

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:32.090
It's going to landfills.

00:12:32.090 --> 00:12:33.610
It's going to incinerators.

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:36.460
And it's being leaked out
into the world's oceans

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:37.660
and the environment.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:39.324
And that leakage
is where I'm going

00:12:39.324 --> 00:12:40.490
to focus for the next while.

00:12:40.490 --> 00:12:43.540
That's really where are our
focus with 5 Gyres has been

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:46.300
for the last eight years or so.

00:12:46.300 --> 00:12:48.970
I saw this in a big
way for my first time

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.740
when I was on the
Big Island of Hawaii.

00:12:50.740 --> 00:12:55.030
Has anyone ever heard of or been
to Junk Beach or Kamilo Beach?

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:56.590
Perhaps seen photos of it?

00:12:56.590 --> 00:12:59.650
Well, this is a unique
beach in that it lies right

00:12:59.650 --> 00:13:01.660
in the heart of where
a lot of currents

00:13:01.660 --> 00:13:05.620
that make up these ocean systems
just bring lots of debris.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:08.590
And it used to actually be a
forging ground for islanders

00:13:08.590 --> 00:13:10.660
looking for logs and
things like that.

00:13:10.660 --> 00:13:12.430
As I walked around
this beach, it

00:13:12.430 --> 00:13:15.460
was like looking at
Walmart washed ashore.

00:13:15.460 --> 00:13:18.640
You can find pretty much
everything that you needed.

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:21.820
And as I looked at the writing
underneath a lot of objects

00:13:21.820 --> 00:13:24.410
here-- shampoo bottles,
and detergent bottles--

00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:28.970
I saw writing in Spanish,
English, Korean, Japanese,

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.290
and Chinese.

00:13:30.290 --> 00:13:33.770
So this is literally washing
up from the entire Pacific Rim.

00:13:33.770 --> 00:13:36.080
I would venture to guess
that very little of this

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.690
is coming from local islanders.

00:13:38.690 --> 00:13:42.300
And it's not just an
environmental ecological issue.

00:13:42.300 --> 00:13:44.120
There's also a human
rights component here

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:45.966
and a social justice component.

00:13:45.966 --> 00:13:47.840
As you see, I'm sure
many people in the world

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:51.170
have had a chance to travel
to some areas that don't yet

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:55.980
have infrastructure to deal
with all of this waste.

00:13:55.980 --> 00:14:00.260
And here you can see a young boy
in Manila in the Philippines.

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:02.150
This river here is so
choked with plastic

00:14:02.150 --> 00:14:03.669
you can't even see the water.

00:14:03.669 --> 00:14:05.210
And he's looking
for anything that he

00:14:05.210 --> 00:14:08.280
might find that has some value.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.000
So here we can look
to really the waste

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.780
picker, this informal sector,
to inform what things really

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:16.980
do have value.

00:14:16.980 --> 00:14:19.370
So going back to the oceans.

00:14:19.370 --> 00:14:22.907
There are five subtropical
gyres, 11 gyres total.

00:14:22.907 --> 00:14:24.740
But I'm going to show
you a current modeling

00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:28.880
study that really shows how
currents in the ocean travel.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:32.630
And this study was conducted
by some scientists at NOAA,

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:35.360
using various modeling,
computer models simulations,

00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:38.750
to figure out where new
drifters travel and accumulate

00:14:38.750 --> 00:14:40.620
over a 20-year period.

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:42.350
So I like to tell
people to imagine

00:14:42.350 --> 00:14:44.550
any one of those
squares is an object.

00:14:44.550 --> 00:14:46.280
And you can track
it around the oceans

00:14:46.280 --> 00:14:52.620
for the next 20 years, half a
year, one year, three years.

00:14:52.620 --> 00:14:56.030
You can see also how quickly
the currents from Japan

00:14:56.030 --> 00:14:58.970
are making a beeline for the
United States and then others

00:14:58.970 --> 00:15:02.330
sort of getting up
into that other gyre,

00:15:02.330 --> 00:15:04.250
the Aleutian currents.

00:15:04.250 --> 00:15:07.370
10 years-- so in 10
years, a single object

00:15:07.370 --> 00:15:11.630
can travel from California
all the way to Japan and back.

00:15:11.630 --> 00:15:15.290
And in 20 years, it starts to
pool in these concentrations

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:18.650
zones that we used to
call garbage patches.

00:15:18.650 --> 00:15:21.190
And we're now referring
to it as more of a smog,

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:23.840
and I'll get more into that.

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:27.300
So you can see here the
five subtropical large gyres

00:15:27.300 --> 00:15:28.885
in the world.

00:15:28.885 --> 00:15:30.260
Now, I want to
focus a little bit

00:15:30.260 --> 00:15:33.050
on what are the
impacts of taking

00:15:33.050 --> 00:15:36.590
this non-biodegradable
fossil fuel material

00:15:36.590 --> 00:15:40.600
and saturating our oceans
with these products.

00:15:40.600 --> 00:15:42.100
So entanglement.

00:15:42.100 --> 00:15:45.100
Now as I mentioned before, some
of the studies on entanglement

00:15:45.100 --> 00:15:47.020
were first reported
back in the '60s.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:49.180
So this has been going
on for a long time,

00:15:49.180 --> 00:15:52.330
and we're only now really
beginning to wake up.

00:15:52.330 --> 00:15:56.680
This snapping turtle
does have a happy ending.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:16:00.730
She was found outside of the
swamps of New Orleans so,

00:16:00.730 --> 00:16:02.290
you know, common
snapping turtle.

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:03.610
And a young boy found her.

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:05.680
So for the young
people in the audience,

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:07.880
you guys can really
make a difference.

00:16:07.880 --> 00:16:09.730
They brought this turtle
to the Audubon Zoo.

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:13.420
They named her Mae West,
for reasons that some of us

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:15.160
will understand.

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:17.740
And they were able to cut that
ring off, and she did survive.

00:16:17.740 --> 00:16:19.510
We brought her back
to Los Angeles,

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:21.970
and she's now at a
wildlife rehab center

00:16:21.970 --> 00:16:23.380
where children can see her.

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:26.350
Because she really tells a story
about how even the small stuff

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:29.080
can have devastating impacts.

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:31.570
And ingestion-- this
is the other big way

00:16:31.570 --> 00:16:33.970
that plastic can
affect marine wildlife.

00:16:33.970 --> 00:16:38.740
Many different species that
feed and forage in the gyres

00:16:38.740 --> 00:16:41.590
are now increasingly
finding our waste competing

00:16:41.590 --> 00:16:44.290
with their natural food source.

00:16:44.290 --> 00:16:46.030
And the numbers are stark.

00:16:46.030 --> 00:16:48.020
These are likely
conservative estimates

00:16:48.020 --> 00:16:50.620
on how many marine
animals are impacted.

00:16:50.620 --> 00:16:53.800
Today it's roughly
over 600 species.

00:16:53.800 --> 00:16:57.400
And the numbers are
probably increasing.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:00.370
I do want to show you,
though, that it's not just

00:17:00.370 --> 00:17:01.270
marine animals.

00:17:01.270 --> 00:17:04.240
And I brought something
to illustrate that here.

00:17:04.240 --> 00:17:06.849
So my husband Marcus, who
co-founded this organization

00:17:06.849 --> 00:17:11.060
with me, had a chance to go to
the deserts outside of Dubai

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:14.589
two years ago, visiting some
of the same places where,

00:17:14.589 --> 00:17:16.540
as a combat veteran, he
served in the Gulf War

00:17:16.540 --> 00:17:20.410
and saw a different side of
the whole fossil fuel issue.

00:17:20.410 --> 00:17:22.720
He brought this back
along with five others.

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:26.260
The one I wanted to bring was so
large that I couldn't carry it.

00:17:26.260 --> 00:17:29.590
This was inside the
stomach of a camel.

00:17:29.590 --> 00:17:32.440
I'll show you the larger one.

00:17:32.440 --> 00:17:35.857
So there are now so
many examples of this.

00:17:35.857 --> 00:17:37.690
The first one that was
sent to us we thought

00:17:37.690 --> 00:17:40.540
was maybe the anomaly, but
we have five of them now.

00:17:40.540 --> 00:17:42.640
And according to some
camel researchers--

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:46.000
they're at the largest
camel center in the world--

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.070
when you find a carcass
of camels today,

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:50.770
you inevitably will find
plastic in their stomachs,

00:17:50.770 --> 00:17:54.070
plastic bags, plastic
packaging, ropes.

00:17:54.070 --> 00:17:55.000
Why do they eat it?

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.130
They may be attracted
to food residue

00:17:57.130 --> 00:17:59.890
or maybe it mimics something
that they might naturally

00:17:59.890 --> 00:18:01.000
eat stuck in trees.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.660
It looks like leaves.

00:18:02.660 --> 00:18:04.870
So the point is that
this is a marine issue

00:18:04.870 --> 00:18:07.600
and a terrestrial issue.

00:18:07.600 --> 00:18:11.670
So I had a chance to see
this firsthand in 2008.

00:18:11.670 --> 00:18:14.860
I had been haunted by
this issue since 2001,

00:18:14.860 --> 00:18:17.980
and I finally got my chance
to join a research expedition

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:21.010
across the North Pacific from
Hawaii all the way back to Los

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:22.600
Angeles.

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:24.760
And what we saw day
after day after day

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:26.620
were samples that
look like this.

00:18:26.620 --> 00:18:29.650
This is actually a sample
from that very journey,

00:18:29.650 --> 00:18:31.870
mostly broken down
confetti mixed

00:18:31.870 --> 00:18:34.240
in with a lot of marine life.

00:18:34.240 --> 00:18:38.200
And when people talk about
the island the size of Texas,

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:40.510
to de-bunk that, what
you see and here,

00:18:40.510 --> 00:18:43.150
it looks like maybe a
handful of confetti.

00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:46.330
We collected over an area maybe
two nautical miles inside.

00:18:46.330 --> 00:18:49.570
So it's incredibly
diffuse, very spread out.

00:18:49.570 --> 00:18:52.270
But it was what we saw at
night that really struck me.

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:55.350
We collected samples during
the day and at night.

00:18:55.350 --> 00:18:58.270
And at night, our samples
were full of life.

00:18:58.270 --> 00:19:00.730
We have the largest
migration of any species

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:02.920
in the world in the
oceans every single day,

00:19:02.920 --> 00:19:05.170
creatures coming up to
feed on zooplankton.

00:19:05.170 --> 00:19:06.610
And now there are
so much plastic

00:19:06.610 --> 00:19:10.180
in their feeding grounds, that
this is what we're seeing.

00:19:10.180 --> 00:19:13.270
This is a myctophid, also
called a lantern fish.

00:19:13.270 --> 00:19:15.400
We brought over 600
of these back to land

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:17.590
and found that roughly
one third of them

00:19:17.590 --> 00:19:20.470
had plastic in their stomachs,
along with the zooplankton they

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:21.670
should be eating.

00:19:21.670 --> 00:19:25.640
Scripps has also done a study
like this, and they found 9%.

00:19:25.640 --> 00:19:29.260
So discrepancy is
probably due to methods

00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:31.030
and how these fish
were collected.

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:33.520
But the point being
we're seeing plastic

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:36.370
in the stomachs of fish that are
extremely important in the food

00:19:36.370 --> 00:19:37.460
chain.

00:19:37.460 --> 00:19:40.900
These fish make up 60% of
the ocean's fish biomass.

00:19:40.900 --> 00:19:42.610
And why we know
this is a problem

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:46.330
is that plastic in the oceans
can absorb contaminants

00:19:46.330 --> 00:19:48.490
at very high
concentrations, things

00:19:48.490 --> 00:19:52.540
like PCBs and DDT, flame
retardants, chemicals

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:54.370
that are hydrophobic--

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:56.680
won't mix with water,
but only oleophilic.

00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:59.380
They'll stick to
oily substances.

00:19:59.380 --> 00:20:02.650
And a single particle of
plastic, the size of a lentil,

00:20:02.650 --> 00:20:06.130
can have up to a million
times higher concentration

00:20:06.130 --> 00:20:09.380
of these pollutants than
the ambient sea water.

00:20:09.380 --> 00:20:14.050
So this was a pretty
profound realization for us.

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:16.300
Two things happened
on that trip--

00:20:16.300 --> 00:20:18.460
seeing the food chain
impacts and then

00:20:18.460 --> 00:20:22.810
also one day when Marcus, who
I had known for a few months,

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:25.600
fished out a piece of derelict
fishing gear on that voyage,

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:28.000
made a little ring and
proposed right there.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.160
And so that was how our
personal and professional

00:20:30.160 --> 00:20:31.870
collided together.

00:20:31.870 --> 00:20:33.940
But he had one big
adventure he wanted

00:20:33.940 --> 00:20:36.520
to do before we got married.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:39.070
And that was to build a
raft out of plastic bottles

00:20:39.070 --> 00:20:41.150
and sail across
those same currents

00:20:41.150 --> 00:20:43.610
and use that as a way
to try and draw new eyes

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:46.770
and ears to this issue.

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:48.260
So there is JUNK.

00:20:48.260 --> 00:20:51.260
That's the boat that we built.
It took two and a half months

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:52.040
to build it.

00:20:52.040 --> 00:20:54.320
It took him three
months to sail it.

00:20:54.320 --> 00:20:56.960
He often quips that he could
have walked faster to Hawaii

00:20:56.960 --> 00:20:59.330
than sail in this boat.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:02.600
We collected 15,000 bottles
from all over Los Angeles

00:21:02.600 --> 00:21:05.960
and had schoolchildren all
over the state helping us

00:21:05.960 --> 00:21:07.370
with the materials.

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:10.070
And the point was to ride
those same currents that

00:21:10.070 --> 00:21:15.380
would take any drifting object
from California out to Hawaii.

00:21:15.380 --> 00:21:17.540
It didn't go as
smoothly as we expected.

00:21:17.540 --> 00:21:20.600
It ended up taking three
months instead of six weeks

00:21:20.600 --> 00:21:21.740
as we had predicted.

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:23.720
They ran really low
on food, and they had

00:21:23.720 --> 00:21:25.630
their worst storm on day four.

00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:27.380
So I'm going to show
you a couple of clips

00:21:27.380 --> 00:21:30.830
from that voyage, including
what happened during that storm

00:21:30.830 --> 00:21:35.180
was that all the labels on their
canned food got washed off.

00:21:35.180 --> 00:21:39.200
And the last video shows a more
sobering look at the food chain

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:41.486
impacts that I spoke about.

