00:24:28.840 --> 00:24:32.320
- So that was a very long summer
for the fiancee back on land.

00:24:32.320 --> 00:24:35.040
I was mission control and
doing the weather reports

00:24:35.040 --> 00:24:37.619
and raising the
funds back on land.

00:24:37.619 --> 00:24:38.910
This is what really shocked us.

00:24:38.910 --> 00:24:41.670
Because we'd seen plastic in the
stomachs of these small fish,

00:24:41.670 --> 00:24:43.909
those myctophid fish
that I shared before.

00:24:43.909 --> 00:24:45.450
But this was the
first time we'd seen

00:24:45.450 --> 00:24:49.620
plastic in the stomachs of fish
that people would normally eat.

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:51.270
Marcus didn't end
up eating this one

00:24:51.270 --> 00:24:53.670
because of what we know
about that transfer,

00:24:53.670 --> 00:24:55.950
that plastics
absorb contaminants

00:24:55.950 --> 00:24:59.310
and that those can then desorb
into the fatty tissues of fish

00:24:59.310 --> 00:25:00.690
and other organisms.

00:25:00.690 --> 00:25:03.770
But the science is going
smaller and smaller on this

00:25:03.770 --> 00:25:06.870
to where we're now seeing
fragments of plastic

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:09.180
in the bodies of
zooplankton, very

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:11.010
important at the base
of the food chain,

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:13.410
and even nanoparticles
of plastic

00:25:13.410 --> 00:25:16.050
inside the circulatory
system of mussels

00:25:16.050 --> 00:25:17.730
and clams and other bivalves.

00:25:17.730 --> 00:25:20.730
And there have even been studies
looking at common shellfish

00:25:20.730 --> 00:25:23.670
eaters and seeing the sum
total of microplastics

00:25:23.670 --> 00:25:26.280
that they're ingesting, because
you eat the whole organism.

00:25:26.280 --> 00:25:28.330
You don't take out the stomach.

00:25:28.330 --> 00:25:30.090
Which brings up the question--

00:25:30.090 --> 00:25:32.880
what impact is this
having on you and I?

00:25:32.880 --> 00:25:36.250
And the science here
still needs a lot of work.

00:25:36.250 --> 00:25:39.510
There are a lot of points in
that puzzle that can be proven.

00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:41.280
But looking at the
whole link to see

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:45.930
how are humans affected by
plastic is challenging still.

00:25:45.930 --> 00:25:48.120
What we do know is that
there's enough evidence

00:25:48.120 --> 00:25:51.490
to suggest that we
proceed with caution.

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:54.120
I was personally interested
in this after Marcus

00:25:54.120 --> 00:25:56.280
and I got married and
thought about having a child.

00:25:56.280 --> 00:25:57.446
You saw the results of that.

00:25:57.446 --> 00:25:59.790
She's healthy and
everything came out fine.

00:25:59.790 --> 00:26:01.710
But when we took a
sample of my blood

00:26:01.710 --> 00:26:05.790
and sent it off to a lab to
be sampled for contaminants,

00:26:05.790 --> 00:26:08.220
we found all four contaminants
that we were looking for.

00:26:08.220 --> 00:26:13.440
We were finding PCBs, DDT, PFCs,
and flame retardants, higher

00:26:13.440 --> 00:26:15.200
levels of flame retardants.

00:26:15.200 --> 00:26:17.700
And it was really interesting
when I got those studies back,

00:26:17.700 --> 00:26:21.450
because a toxicologist
helped me color code them

00:26:21.450 --> 00:26:24.670
for where I fell on the national
spectrum-- green for good,

00:26:24.670 --> 00:26:29.130
or orange for so-so,
and red for not good.

00:26:29.130 --> 00:26:32.340
And I was green for three
out of the four contaminants.

00:26:32.340 --> 00:26:33.630
And at first I celebrated.

00:26:33.630 --> 00:26:37.200
It was almost like getting
good grades back on an exam.

00:26:37.200 --> 00:26:39.030
But then I thought
this is just crazy

00:26:39.030 --> 00:26:40.420
that this is the new baseline.

00:26:40.420 --> 00:26:42.720
This is the new normal
that every single one of us

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:44.910
has these contaminants
in our body

00:26:44.910 --> 00:26:47.280
and that the flame retardants
were slightly higher

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:48.780
being a Californian.

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:53.040
Now, again we have so much that
we don't understand about this.

00:26:53.040 --> 00:26:57.000
It's very difficult to say that
there's a cause and effect.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:00.060
We also don't know how do these
chemicals interact with one

00:27:00.060 --> 00:27:01.590
another inside the human body?

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:05.070
There are studies looking at
those chemicals and isolation.

00:27:05.070 --> 00:27:07.560
But again, my personal
feeling, and a lot

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:11.592
of sentiment shared by
people in this field,

00:27:11.592 --> 00:27:13.050
are that we have
enough information

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:15.660
to suggest that we
proceed with caution,

00:27:15.660 --> 00:27:17.820
that the burden of
responsibility for proving

00:27:17.820 --> 00:27:21.570
that these chemicals are safe
should be put on industry

00:27:21.570 --> 00:27:23.040
and corporations
and should not be

00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:25.500
placed on the general public.

00:27:25.500 --> 00:27:28.080
So these ideas were
swirling around for us

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.690
when we decided we
need to get more

00:27:30.690 --> 00:27:32.550
information about this issue.

00:27:32.550 --> 00:27:34.200
We'd seen a lot
of research thanks

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:37.230
to Captain Charles Moore about
plastic in the North Pacific,

00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:39.600
but there was zero
research on plastic

00:27:39.600 --> 00:27:41.520
in the southern
hemisphere gyres.

00:27:41.520 --> 00:27:45.810
So this was our inspiration
to launch a new organization

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:47.580
and sail around
the world looking

00:27:47.580 --> 00:27:49.940
at this issue of
plastic pollution.

00:27:49.940 --> 00:27:53.160
So part of what we did was
invite the public to join,

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:55.400
and this is something that
we still do, is invite

00:27:55.400 --> 00:27:59.730
other scientists, filmmakers,
students, teachers, artists,

00:27:59.730 --> 00:28:01.860
musicians, and even
heads of companies,

00:28:01.860 --> 00:28:05.390
including people from the
industry, to come with us,

00:28:05.390 --> 00:28:08.120
roll up their sleeves,
get their hands dirty,

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.100
participate in the
science, and then go back

00:28:10.100 --> 00:28:12.590
to their communities
to be ambassadors.

00:28:12.590 --> 00:28:15.170
So I'm going to share
another short video,

00:28:15.170 --> 00:28:16.640
very low production quality.

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:19.802
This was iPhone and
laptop on a boat.

00:28:19.802 --> 00:28:21.260
But this gives an
idea of what it's

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:23.180
like to be out in the
middle of the ocean

00:28:23.180 --> 00:28:26.990
and see evidence of
plastic contaminating

00:28:26.990 --> 00:28:28.670
some really remote regions.

00:28:28.670 --> 00:28:30.542
This was also our honeymoon.

00:28:30.542 --> 00:28:32.367
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:28:32.367 --> 00:28:33.200
