00:30:31.730 --> 00:30:33.550
So I could show
hundreds of photos

00:30:33.550 --> 00:30:35.080
that all pretty
much look like this,

00:30:35.080 --> 00:30:37.210
and this is a typical sample.

00:30:37.210 --> 00:30:39.370
This one is from
the South Atlantic.

00:30:39.370 --> 00:30:42.760
You can see just this mixture
of life, Portuguese man-of-war,

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:45.700
mixed in with these
fragments of plastic

00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:49.420
that are impossible to really
attribute to any source.

00:30:49.420 --> 00:30:51.700
We can't tell what
product these came from,

00:30:51.700 --> 00:30:53.390
what country they came from.

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:56.500
So coming up with solutions
can be challenging

00:30:56.500 --> 00:30:58.630
when you're looking
at microplastics.

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:02.620
But when we took all of our
data from all five gyres

00:31:02.620 --> 00:31:04.570
and other hot spots
around the world

00:31:04.570 --> 00:31:07.090
and paired it with data
from seven other scientists

00:31:07.090 --> 00:31:08.710
from regions around
the world, we

00:31:08.710 --> 00:31:11.590
were able to come up with
the first global estimate

00:31:11.590 --> 00:31:13.690
of plastic floating
in the oceans.

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:16.750
Now, this is very different from
plastic entering the oceans.

00:31:16.750 --> 00:31:21.700
But this is what we found,
roughly 270,000 metric tons

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:24.790
made up of 5.25
trillion particles.

00:31:24.790 --> 00:31:26.640
And that, I think, is
the important part.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:29.350
Who can visualize 5.25
trillion particles?

00:31:29.350 --> 00:31:31.000
None of us.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:33.160
But the point is that we
can't go out to the oceans

00:31:33.160 --> 00:31:34.300
to clean up this problem.

00:31:34.300 --> 00:31:37.810
You can't skim the ocean
of 5.25 trillion particles

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:39.550
without removing so
much life that you'd

00:31:39.550 --> 00:31:41.510
be probably doing more damage.

00:31:41.510 --> 00:31:44.260
We've got to go upstream and
solve this problem closer

00:31:44.260 --> 00:31:45.760
to the source of
the problem, which

00:31:45.760 --> 00:31:47.470
really with any
environmental problem

00:31:47.470 --> 00:31:50.980
is a much more efficient
way to go than cleanup.

00:31:50.980 --> 00:31:52.850
So this caused us to
look at it differently.

00:31:52.850 --> 00:31:54.670
Instead of calling
it a Garbage Patch

00:31:54.670 --> 00:31:56.740
to call it a Plastic Smog.

00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:58.780
And we would apply the
same kind of thinking

00:31:58.780 --> 00:32:00.160
to dealing with smog.

00:32:00.160 --> 00:32:03.040
You wouldn't clean it up with
vacuum cleaners in the air.

00:32:03.040 --> 00:32:04.720
You would look at
smarter, emissions,

00:32:04.720 --> 00:32:07.790
and smarter vehicles,
and smarter technology,

00:32:07.790 --> 00:32:10.450
better ways of design.

00:32:10.450 --> 00:32:12.850
Really, it's about design.

00:32:12.850 --> 00:32:15.370
So I want to share
one example of how

00:32:15.370 --> 00:32:17.470
we can use science,
in this case,

00:32:17.470 --> 00:32:19.690
to actually drive a solution.

00:32:19.690 --> 00:32:21.310
And we'd been around
the world looking

00:32:21.310 --> 00:32:24.880
at plastic in many of
the world's oceans.

00:32:24.880 --> 00:32:27.700
And engaging people who don't
live directly on an ocean

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:28.880
can be challenging.

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:31.757
Even though we all know that
we need oceans for health,

00:32:31.757 --> 00:32:34.090
it can be hard to engage
people to care about the coasts

00:32:34.090 --> 00:32:36.820
if they're not right
connected to an ocean.

00:32:36.820 --> 00:32:39.970
So that inspired us to go
into the Great Lakes in 2012

00:32:39.970 --> 00:32:42.190
to do the same sort of research.

00:32:42.190 --> 00:32:45.370
We spend 2012 and
2013 serving all five

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:47.050
of the Great Lakes
in partnership

00:32:47.050 --> 00:32:50.234
with a great scientist from
SUNY Fredonia, Dr. Sam Mason.

00:32:50.234 --> 00:32:52.150
And I'm going to share
with you what we found.

00:32:52.150 --> 00:32:54.040
It wasn't at all
what we expected.

00:32:54.040 --> 00:32:57.040
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:01.060
- There are a lot of reasons why
we should protect our oceans.

00:33:01.060 --> 00:33:04.270
They give us oxygen. They
regulate our climate.

00:33:04.270 --> 00:33:05.770
Our oceans give us food.

00:33:09.150 --> 00:33:14.440
But what's really going on
is we've turned our oceans

00:33:14.440 --> 00:33:15.940
into a plastic smog.

00:33:15.940 --> 00:33:18.910
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:33:33.779 --> 00:33:36.070
We set out with a mission to
research plastic pollution

00:33:36.070 --> 00:33:39.070
in all five oceans and then
leverage those findings back

00:33:39.070 --> 00:33:41.595
to land to drive solutions.

00:33:41.595 --> 00:33:42.970
- We began in the
North Atlantic,

00:33:42.970 --> 00:33:45.880
was our first
expedition in 2010,

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:48.630
did the South Atlantic
across the Indian Ocean,

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:51.850
the South Pacific,
Chile to Easter Island,

00:33:51.850 --> 00:33:55.450
then up to North Pacific,
finding microplastics

00:33:55.450 --> 00:33:58.220
in 21% of the planet's surface.

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:05.360
Out there in the
oceans, you really

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:09.860
can't identify the product,
because it's so broken down.

00:34:09.860 --> 00:34:13.159
I mean, how do you solve
the problem with this?

00:34:13.159 --> 00:34:15.530
I can't point to a company.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:17.150
I can't point to a country.

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:19.340
You've got to get
closer to land,

00:34:19.340 --> 00:34:21.139
into our rivers and lakes.

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:26.810
- So we went into
the Great Lakes

00:34:26.810 --> 00:34:29.360
doing the same research,
the same methods that we've

00:34:29.360 --> 00:34:31.059
used in all five oceans.

00:34:31.059 --> 00:34:32.600
- There we could
point to a country--

00:34:32.600 --> 00:34:35.030
if we found something,
Canada and the United States

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:38.449
share those waters.

00:34:38.449 --> 00:34:41.900
We began to find these
small, perfectly round

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:46.250
little spheres, one
third millimeter in size.

00:34:46.250 --> 00:34:50.699
I had never seen that
anyplace else in the world.

00:34:50.699 --> 00:34:53.840
We had a hunch what they were,
went to your local pharmacy.

00:34:53.840 --> 00:34:55.550
We got the facial
scrubs, the one that

00:34:55.550 --> 00:34:58.120
even say microbeads
on the front,

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:01.012
put them through a sieve.

00:35:01.012 --> 00:35:03.790
And there they were.

00:35:03.790 --> 00:35:06.590
They matched.

00:35:06.590 --> 00:35:09.140
Polyethylene and
polypropylene-- it's

00:35:09.140 --> 00:35:13.490
a designed microplastic
that goes on your face,

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:16.893
down the drain, out to our
rivers, lakes, into the ocean.

00:35:16.893 --> 00:35:19.851
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:38.380
The ocean's surface is not
the final resting place

00:35:38.380 --> 00:35:40.150
for microplastics.

00:35:40.150 --> 00:35:42.620
It's settling to the
sea floor, but it's also

00:35:42.620 --> 00:35:47.620
disappearing via the stomachs
of animals that consume it.

00:35:47.620 --> 00:35:50.620
- A tiny particle of plastic
the size of a microbead

00:35:50.620 --> 00:35:53.860
may look like a fish egg for
many different organisms.

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:55.990
Each one of these
particles of plastic

00:35:55.990 --> 00:35:57.850
is like a sponge
for contaminants,

00:35:57.850 --> 00:36:00.220
things like PCBs or DDT.

00:36:00.220 --> 00:36:03.310
Many different toxic
chemicals can be absorbed

00:36:03.310 --> 00:36:06.460
by plastic in the ocean.

00:36:06.460 --> 00:36:09.760
- It's not just, you know, one
bird, one whale, and one fish.

00:36:09.760 --> 00:36:12.830
It's ecosystem-wide.

00:36:12.830 --> 00:36:15.090
They're eating
all those plastics

00:36:15.090 --> 00:36:25.130
that go up the food
chain back to you and I.

00:36:25.130 --> 00:36:26.660
- Whether or not
we're a fish eater,

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:29.840
we all depend on the
oceans for health.

00:36:29.840 --> 00:36:33.470
Everyone has a local
lake, stream, or a river,

00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:36.620
or a watershed that
they care about.

00:36:36.620 --> 00:36:38.600
- We can change our
throwaway culture,

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:40.820
the way we treat each
other and the environment,

00:36:40.820 --> 00:36:44.330
and make it much better
than it was last century.

00:36:44.330 --> 00:36:46.890
You start with these, facial
cleansers and toothpastes.

00:36:46.890 --> 00:36:50.450
These microbeads, these designed
microplastics which you cannot

00:36:50.450 --> 00:36:56.050
recycle at all, that's a design
that needs to be changed.

00:36:56.050 --> 00:36:58.140
That starts with us and
our purchasing power.

00:36:58.140 --> 00:37:00.440
So zero waste your
plastic footprint.

00:37:05.617 --> 00:37:06.200
[END PLAYBACK]

00:37:06.200 --> 00:37:07.880
- I'm going to skip
the ending part.

00:37:07.880 --> 00:37:11.810
This is the sample that
caused us to really pause.

00:37:11.810 --> 00:37:15.020
This one sample had more plastic
than any of the ocean samples

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:16.590
we'd looked at
anywhere in the world.

00:37:16.590 --> 00:37:18.620
And now you know the
rest of that story.

00:37:18.620 --> 00:37:21.182
We published those results
in a peer reviewed journal,

00:37:21.182 --> 00:37:22.890
and we thought that
that would be enough.

00:37:22.890 --> 00:37:26.840
We called the vice president
at Procter &amp; Gamble

00:37:26.840 --> 00:37:28.310
and presented our findings.

00:37:28.310 --> 00:37:30.740
And what they said was, you
need to do more research.

00:37:30.740 --> 00:37:33.860
Until you can prove that
it's our products going

00:37:33.860 --> 00:37:36.780
into these waters, then we're
not going to do anything.

00:37:36.780 --> 00:37:39.620
What was really interesting
is that during this time,

00:37:39.620 --> 00:37:42.290
I found out that they've known
about this for a long time.

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:44.720
I found an internal document
that was on the web.

00:37:44.720 --> 00:37:46.520
I saved it, because
it's not there anymore,

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:51.320
basically saying that we
recognize that these beads may

00:37:51.320 --> 00:37:52.824
be entering the
aquatic environment

00:37:52.824 --> 00:37:54.740
and that we will probably
need to do something

00:37:54.740 --> 00:37:56.540
about this at some point.

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:59.380
Well, we didn't want
to wait for that point.

00:37:59.380 --> 00:38:01.880
When we heard you need
to do more research,

00:38:01.880 --> 00:38:03.710
we decided to go legislative.

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:05.780
We hired an attorney
in San Francisco.

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:09.080
We co-drafted a bill, and we
presented it in California.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:12.260
And in 2014, we came
devastatingly close,

00:38:12.260 --> 00:38:14.460
lost by two Senate votes.

00:38:14.460 --> 00:38:19.626
Meantime, Illinois passed
a bill that everyone

00:38:19.626 --> 00:38:21.500
jumped up and down and
got all excited about,

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:24.410
and the same bill language
was spreading from state

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:25.654
to state to state.

00:38:25.654 --> 00:38:27.320
And what people didn't
know is that this

00:38:27.320 --> 00:38:30.650
had a huge loophole,
that basically changed

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:32.060
the entire spirit of the bill.

00:38:32.060 --> 00:38:35.060
Way down in the draft,
that very few people read

00:38:35.060 --> 00:38:38.810
in the definitions, how they
defined plastic microbeads was

00:38:38.810 --> 00:38:42.590
any intentionally added
non-biodegradable--

00:38:42.590 --> 00:38:45.170
so just by putting in that
non-biodegradable piece,

00:38:45.170 --> 00:38:48.480
they opened up the door
to put in bioplastics.

00:38:48.480 --> 00:38:50.140
PLA does not break down.

00:38:50.140 --> 00:38:53.089
PLA is one kind of
bioplastic made from corn.

00:38:53.089 --> 00:38:55.130
It does not break down in
the marine environment.

00:38:55.130 --> 00:38:57.710
It needs a high heat
municipal composting facility,

00:38:57.710 --> 00:38:59.660
and even then, a
lot of recyclers

00:38:59.660 --> 00:39:01.520
tell us that they
don't want them.

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:04.010
So that was pretty underhanded.

00:39:04.010 --> 00:39:05.870
We kept on with the
battle, and what really

00:39:05.870 --> 00:39:09.230
made a difference in 2015
was getting a full coalition

00:39:09.230 --> 00:39:10.310
on board.

00:39:10.310 --> 00:39:12.350
And this, again,
just underscores

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:15.650
the power of collaboration, when
lots of NGOs and policymakers

00:39:15.650 --> 00:39:17.000
come together.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:18.350
And students played a role here.

00:39:18.350 --> 00:39:21.020
These students at UCLA
spent three months

00:39:21.020 --> 00:39:23.000
getting microbeads out
of their student store.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:25.760
And that made a difference
as we were fighting

00:39:25.760 --> 00:39:27.830
this fight in California.

00:39:27.830 --> 00:39:31.790
And then finally, after we
passed the bill in California,

00:39:31.790 --> 00:39:34.960
this really laid down the
momentum for a federal bill.

00:39:34.960 --> 00:39:38.630
And in the final
days, weeks of 2015,

00:39:38.630 --> 00:39:41.750
President Obama signed the
Microbead-Free Waters Act,

00:39:41.750 --> 00:39:42.920
a federal bill.

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:46.650
So that was great news,
but it's not enough.

00:39:46.650 --> 00:39:49.850
The plastic pollution movement
celebrates these victories.

00:39:49.850 --> 00:39:50.810
We ban bags.

00:39:50.810 --> 00:39:52.160
We ban beads.

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:54.810
But how are we really
going to move the needle?

00:39:54.810 --> 00:39:57.800
And I want to share a couple
more examples of solutions.

00:39:57.800 --> 00:40:00.830
How are we going to move
towards a circular economy?

00:40:00.830 --> 00:40:04.130
And this is a concept that's
now really getting traction.

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:05.870
Instead of the way
we do things now,

00:40:05.870 --> 00:40:08.030
we take products
that are largely

00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:10.760
toxic in the environment,
in a linear fashion,

00:40:10.760 --> 00:40:13.820
we produce products that
mostly go to the landfill.

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:16.160
And how can we change that idea?

00:40:16.160 --> 00:40:19.460
So we thought instead of
picking off products one by one,

00:40:19.460 --> 00:40:21.380
we came together
with a couple of NGOs

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:24.520
and produced a first
draft of the ban list.

00:40:24.520 --> 00:40:26.660
And that was taking
available data

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:29.480
on coastal cleanups
and waste management

00:40:29.480 --> 00:40:31.820
and trying to pair it
together to come up with, what

00:40:31.820 --> 00:40:36.440
are the 10 to 15 worst products
that we just need to get rid of

00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:39.570
and redesign and back
it up with good data?

00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:42.230
And one of the things we came
to is a large majority of those

00:40:42.230 --> 00:40:44.570
were polystyrene.

00:40:44.570 --> 00:40:47.480
So this is a campaign
that we are launching now,

00:40:47.480 --> 00:40:49.820
and a lot of groups
around the world

00:40:49.820 --> 00:40:51.800
are really looking
at polystyrene

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:56.030
due to its high toxicity and
due to its low recoverability

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:57.950
and recyclability.

00:40:57.950 --> 00:41:00.711
And so this is just an example
of what we're trying to do

00:41:00.711 --> 00:41:02.210
is we're trying to
really facilitate

00:41:02.210 --> 00:41:04.470
people taking local action.

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:07.580
And I think especially now with
our current political status,

00:41:07.580 --> 00:41:10.520
it's reminding us of why we
need to get even deeper involved

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:11.877
in our local politics.

00:41:11.877 --> 00:41:14.210
And I was pleased to see that
you have a number of bills

00:41:14.210 --> 00:41:16.850
here in Massachusetts,
including a statewide bill

00:41:16.850 --> 00:41:20.220
to ban polystyrene.

00:41:20.220 --> 00:41:22.900
Another key part of
the solution is really

00:41:22.900 --> 00:41:25.360
putting the onus, as I
said in the very beginning,

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:27.040
back on producers.

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:29.680
So producers need to
take responsibility

00:41:29.680 --> 00:41:31.180
for what happens
to these products

00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:33.070
after they leave their hands.

00:41:33.070 --> 00:41:35.550
And there's a big fight
here, you can see,

00:41:35.550 --> 00:41:39.370
this map that shows where
we have EPR as of 2015.

00:41:39.370 --> 00:41:42.280
And there seems to be a little
bit of a desert in the United

00:41:42.280 --> 00:41:43.060
States.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:46.060
But fortunately, there are new
bills being introduced now.

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:47.710
There's a lot of
opposition to this

00:41:47.710 --> 00:41:50.140
because they don't want
to pay for the recovery

00:41:50.140 --> 00:41:51.130
of these products.

00:41:51.130 --> 00:41:53.560
But the fight is on, and
I'm hopeful that this will

00:41:53.560 --> 00:41:55.570
happen in the coming years.

00:41:55.570 --> 00:41:58.650
Better design-- how can
we engage corporations

00:41:58.650 --> 00:42:00.430
in involuntary design?

00:42:00.430 --> 00:42:03.282
No one wants to spend
five, 10, 15 years,

00:42:03.282 --> 00:42:04.990
fighting these
legislative battles, which

00:42:04.990 --> 00:42:06.160
we'll continue to do.

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:08.440
But when companies--
like this is a product

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:09.900
that Rainbow Light put out.

00:42:09.900 --> 00:42:10.400
It's.

00:42:10.400 --> 00:42:13.000
A 100% post-consumer
recycled plastic.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:15.340
And if we can incentivize
the recovery of that,

00:42:15.340 --> 00:42:16.910
that's a great place to start.

00:42:16.910 --> 00:42:18.250
I came across this recently.

00:42:18.250 --> 00:42:21.430
It's just in the concept
phase, but the idea

00:42:21.430 --> 00:42:24.490
being, create packaging that
when you're done with a product

00:42:24.490 --> 00:42:25.780
doesn't exist anymore.

00:42:25.780 --> 00:42:28.270
So this concept of
disappearing packaging, this

00:42:28.270 --> 00:42:31.960
is one example of where
the package is the product.

00:42:31.960 --> 00:42:33.850
This is a thesis
project from a student.

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:36.820
I'm really hoping that
this will come to fruition.

00:42:36.820 --> 00:42:39.760
But this is the kind of thinking
that we need really to get out

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:42.070
of our packaging dilemma.

00:42:42.070 --> 00:42:45.220
Better systems-- can we
come up with new systems

00:42:45.220 --> 00:42:47.020
in how we deliver goods?

00:42:47.020 --> 00:42:49.590
For example, sharing--
this is a project

00:42:49.590 --> 00:42:50.800
to New York to the left.

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:52.900
Not only is there a
bikeshare happening here,

00:42:52.900 --> 00:42:54.130
but there's a vessel share.

00:42:54.130 --> 00:42:55.630
The company is called Vessel.

00:42:55.630 --> 00:42:58.064
And the idea is, you
go to a coffee shop.

00:42:58.064 --> 00:42:59.980
You pick up your vessel,
and you can return it

00:42:59.980 --> 00:43:01.870
at the next coffee
shop, because we're all

00:43:01.870 --> 00:43:02.980
busy forgetful people.

00:43:02.980 --> 00:43:04.490
We don't always remember.

00:43:04.490 --> 00:43:07.180
Can we come up with
new ways of doing this?

00:43:07.180 --> 00:43:10.990
Same thing in Portland, where
this similar concept with to-go

00:43:10.990 --> 00:43:13.270
wear, with to-go packaging,
where you can pick it up

00:43:13.270 --> 00:43:15.970
at one place, return it
at another, and get rid

00:43:15.970 --> 00:43:17.980
of all that packaging waste.

00:43:17.980 --> 00:43:19.690
And refillable, of course--

00:43:19.690 --> 00:43:23.080
coming up with new ways that
we can avoid packaging entirely

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:27.000
and just bring in our own
containers and get our goods.

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:31.120
Some post-consumer examples--
you know, again, none of these

00:43:31.120 --> 00:43:32.620
alone are going to
move the needle.

00:43:32.620 --> 00:43:36.220
But together, if we can come up
with more creative approaches--

00:43:36.220 --> 00:43:38.440
to the left is a
company called Bureo,

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:41.080
that are taking
back fishing nets

00:43:41.080 --> 00:43:43.060
from all over the coast
of Chile and moving

00:43:43.060 --> 00:43:46.210
on to other countries,
grinding it up, and turning it

00:43:46.210 --> 00:43:48.760
into products like
skateboards, and sunglasses,

00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:50.320
and other durables.

00:43:50.320 --> 00:43:53.590
On the right, I put an example
from a bigger corporation

00:43:53.590 --> 00:43:55.370
that I haven't
thoroughly vetted.

00:43:55.370 --> 00:43:58.846
So I don't yet know how
they're defining beach plastic,

00:43:58.846 --> 00:44:00.970
but this is a new product
that Head &amp; Shoulders has

00:44:00.970 --> 00:44:05.020
put out that is, in
theory, 100% recyclable

00:44:05.020 --> 00:44:06.790
and made with beach plastic.

00:44:06.790 --> 00:44:10.380
More research there needed,
but I did want to share this.

00:44:10.380 --> 00:44:13.690
And moving away from fossil
fuels entirely as a feedstock--

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:17.470
putting more research into
truly compostable, biodegradable

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:20.800
plastics that can be made
from mushrooms or from algae

00:44:20.800 --> 00:44:24.640
or from shrimp or from compost.

00:44:24.640 --> 00:44:28.690
The point being, we will need
to get away from fossil fuels.

00:44:28.690 --> 00:44:31.210
And finally, getting
the community involved--

00:44:31.210 --> 00:44:32.560
the power of artwork.

00:44:32.560 --> 00:44:35.280
So when we were doing
the microbeads campaign,

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:37.540
Marcus, who's also a
sculptor, created this piece

00:44:37.540 --> 00:44:38.890
called "Anthropocene."

00:44:38.890 --> 00:44:39.980
It's pretty massive.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:43.360
It's a big steel ring
with the Vitruvian Man,

00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:47.650
four bikes power LED
lights, and water

00:44:47.650 --> 00:44:51.010
that is inside, that is
filled with microplastics.

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:54.400
And the tubes of water go
in and around the man's body

00:44:54.400 --> 00:44:58.060
to show this connection between
microplastics and human health.

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:00.652
And some artwork that you
will see out in the lobby

00:45:00.652 --> 00:45:02.860
